<h2><strong>How to Use the Binder on the Wedding Day</strong></h2>
<p>Assembling the binder is half the job. Using it effectively is the other half.</p>
<p><strong>Who Holds the Binder?</strong> The lead planner or coordinator keeps the master. A backup copy goes with an assistant or trusted family member — essential for DIY couples without a professional coordinator.</p>
<p><strong>Briefing VIPs:</strong> Walk through the simplified one-page timeline at the rehearsal. Email or hand out abbreviated versions to the wedding party so everyone knows their role and timing without needing access to the full document.</p>
<p><strong>Day-Of Rhythms:</strong> Check the binder at natural breaks: after hair and makeup, before ceremony line-up, before reception formalities. Confirm next steps against the wedding itinerary rather than relying on memory.</p>
<p><strong>Logging Changes:</strong> Use quick handwritten notes or sticky flags for time shifts (e.g., toasts pushed from 7:35 to 7:45 p.m.). Small adjustments are inevitable — capture them so the whole team stays aligned.</p>
<p><strong>End-of-Night Handoff:</strong> Review the end-of-night checklist before leaving the venue. Sign off with the venue manager and confirm all rented items, personal décor, and gifts have been accounted for.</p>
