<p><strong>How many copies of the wedding day binder should we have?</strong></p>
<p>Have at least two physical copies: one master for the lead planner or day-of coordinator, and one backup for an assistant or trusted family member. Keep one digital copy in a shared drive and share a PDF with key vendors 1–2 weeks before the wedding. For digital sharing and easy collaboration, consider using Google Drive to ensure everyone has access to the latest version. eydn stores your planning documents centrally, making it easy to export and share the right version with the right people at the right time.</p>
<p><strong>Do we still need a binder if we’re using a wedding planning app?</strong></p>
<p>Yes — and they work best together. Apps excel at planning and communication throughout the process, but Wi-Fi and battery issues on-site make a physical binder a reliable backup. The smart approach is to use Eydn throughout planning to stay organized, then export your timeline, vendor contacts, and guest snapshot into a printed binder for the day itself. Digital systems supported by printed run sheets are the most resilient combination.</p>
<p><strong>What size and format should the wedding day binder be?</strong></p>
<p>Use a sturdy three-ring binder in US letter size (8.5 x 11 inches) with a spine label showing the couple’s name and wedding date. Add plastic sheet protectors for contracts and floor plans, and tabbed dividers for each major section. Color-coded tabs make navigation faster under pressure and help keep everything organized. For planners, a neutral branded binder style reusable across multiple weddings with custom covers is worth the investment.</p>
<p><strong>Who should have access to the full binder rather than the abbreviated versions?</strong></p>
<p>The full binder is for the planner, coordinator, and venue manager — it contains contracts, budget notes, and private contact numbers that don’t need to circulate widely. Distribute abbreviated versions to the wedding party (simplified timeline and responsibilities), immediate family (ceremony timing and portrait schedule), and vendors (role-specific run sheets only). Eydn’s sharing settings let you control exactly which details go to which people digitally, mirroring the same logic for the printed version.</p>
<p><strong>Can the binder help if something goes wrong on the day?</strong></p>
<p>Absolutely — that’s one of its core functions. The vendor directory resolves “who do I call?” in seconds. The contracts tab resolves disputes about what was agreed. The logistics tab covers medical emergencies, weather contingencies, and transportation issues. The checklists ensure nothing gets left behind at the end of the night. A wedding planning binder can help keep vendor information, timelines, and checklists organized, making it an essential tool for managing unexpected issues. A well-built binder turns potential chaos into a manageable problem with a clear next step.</p>
<p><strong>What if we’re working with a planner?</strong></p>
<p>If you’re working with a full-service planner, they will manage all aspects of wedding planning, including organization, timelines, vendor coordination, and strategic guidance. They typically maintain and update the wedding day binder for you, ensuring every detail is covered and accessible when needed.</p>
